# Decide the Availability Shape Within Tailnet Resources

## Step

Critical search must survive a Flagg reboot using only flagg, panda, and the two NAS machines. Grill Joel to a decision among (diagnosis § Restore critical availability):

1. A bounded critical operator-search projection served from an always-on host (panda or a NAS) that does not reboot with Flagg, with session search in a separate bounded index.
2. A real three-node Typesense cluster across the tailnet (flagg + panda + NAS) with health-aware clients. Two nodes are not HA.
3. Defer engine replacement unless the bounded split misses the restart budget (stays latent).

Settle in the same grilling: what "critical search" contains as a bounded document set, which host serves it, and who maintains it after the effort closes. Stress-test with the concrete scenario: Flagg reboots at 14:28, what does operator search do at 14:29?

## Result (2026-07-19)

Joel locked in SQLite ("sqlite it is, lock it in"). The shape:

**Critical search** — the critical projection (observations, memory recall, knowledge/vault, operational lookups) lives in one SQLite FTS5 database. Flagg is the only writer. The file replicates to **both** NAS boxes (soon physically separated), each serving it read-only through a small shim. Clients walk an ordered fallback — flagg → NAS-A → NAS-B — no quorum, no leader election. SQLite's durable on-disk indexes mean zero rebuild on any restart.

**Session search** — two-tier. Tier 1: the observer layer (distilled observations) rides in the critical projection and links back to Run IDs. Tier 2: full transcripts in a separate SQLite FTS5 index on flagg, built from the compacted manifest Run set; ripgrep over raw JSONL is the last-ditch fallback. `run_chunks_dev` leaves Typesense entirely.

**Typesense** — demoted to flagg-only, non-critical collections (telemetry etc.). Its failure mode drops from "operator is blind" to "telemetry search is down".

Rejected: a 3-node Typesense cluster (Raft across residential links between physical sites will flap; a stale read replica beats a flapping cluster), and Typesense export/import replicas on the NAS boxes (a permanent bespoke pipeline to avoid a one-time adapter port). Panda is decommissioning and was ruled out as a host.

Consequences: [Build and Validate the Compacted Collection](./build-compacted-collection.svx) retargets from a Typesense collection to the session FTS5 index; the generic implement step splits into [Port Critical Search to SQLite](./port-critical-search-to-sqlite.svx) and [Replicate the Critical DB to Both NAS Boxes](./replicate-critical-db-to-nas.svx); off-site raw JSONL backup goes latent on the brief.
